postcontent:
SOLD: Montana rifle co. made 7 mm wsm with stainless fluted barrel. beautiful wood.tack driving, elk killing machine. custom thru and thru.scope does NOT come with gun. can add one, if need be. 

from the website:
When we first thought about building custom rifles we wanted a line of rifles that addressed a few basic needs. First, with the kind of hunting we like to do, they had to be light. And most important was that light rifles had to be accurate. By nature light rifles are inaccurate because most light contours suffer from "barrel whip". However with the barrel shank design coupled with the M1999 breaching system there is a much stronger base for which to control barrel whip. Another problem we faced was with the extreme hunting we like to do, we run into many harsh conditions. Conditions like rain, sleet, snow and temperature ranges from 110 degrees to well below zero. These are often prime conditions for some of the the best hunting and we wanted our gear to be able to handle those elements. With this we use ALL stainless steel barrels and the complete action is made up of entirely stainless steel parts. We then couple that with some of the best synthetic stocks in the industry, Pendleton Composite's (Oregunsmithing). On top of that for the Ridgeline, Timberline and Alpine we also have the barreled action set in a Ceramic coating for maximum protection. This coating is extremely rugged and durable and will protect the steel from just about any type of weather.

All high country series rifles will be pillar and glass bedded, with all stainless steel barreled actions

Up for sale is a pistol that you don't see on  the market very frequently.  It's an Italian made Beretta model 70S, also known as the "Puma".  According to the web, it's "AI" date stamp places it as a 1982 manufacture from Beretta in Italy, and it was imported by the Berben Corporation out of New York.   It's a single action pistol, with a very smooth safety, a crisp trigger pull, and  it's extremely accurate.   I bought it over a month ago in the hopes that my wife would like it, but she's happy with her smaller Beretta in 25acp.   That being said, it's just going to sit in my safe until the end of days.  I'd like to recoup my investment and purchase something else.

I've put 100 rounds of various 380 FMJ loads through it, and it cycled flawlessly.  I also fired a 20rd  box of the Winchester PDX1 Hollow Points through it, and it didn't skip a beat.  

When I bought this last month I did a lot of searching online for price comparison.  I found Pumas in comparable condition going for around $500, and some extremely worn out Century Arms imports going for around $400.   Please check out gunbroker.com, auctionarms.com or gunsamerica.com if you'd like to verify.  There are only a handful of Model 70s Pumas chambered in 380 on each site.

I am going out of town on Sunday 8 Dec for a few days, so please be patient if you contact me after I depart.
